"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-bobby-finke-saves-century-old-streak-usa-swimming-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 There has been plenty of talk about the waves created by theshallower-than-normal Olympic pool. But on the final night of the swimming competition here, the pool created something different\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094emotional whiplash for the Americans.  Bobby Finke\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s all-guts world record in the 1,500-meter freestyle was a massively clutch swim that kept alive the U.S. streak of at least one individual men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gold medal in the pool since 1900. It was followed by a sobering, first-time-in-Olympic-history loss for the U.S. men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medley relay, with the dethroning delivered by a Chinese team dogged by doping controversies. And then that gave way to a powerful, walk-off world record by the American women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medley relay.  Fin, as they say in French.  Now the reckoning begins.  The final day was an appropriate mixed bag of results for a wildly uneven, largely disappointing U.S. performance. USA Swimming can point to winning both the gold medal and overall medal tallies, with eight golds and 28 total medals to Australia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s seven golds and 18 total medals. After losing the gold-medal tally 13-7 to the Aussies at World Championships last year,\\u00c2\\u00a0 that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s at least one embarrassment reversed. Barely.  But here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the bigger picture: eight golds is the fewest by the Americans in the pool since 1988, and the 28 total is the fewest since 2004. And keep in mind, three events and nine medal chances have been added since 2020.  Nobody expected this to be an easy swimming Olympics for the country that has historically dominated. But hopes were raised after a fast performance at U.S. Olympic trials in June in Indianapolis, and then the Americans failed to follow through in France.  Times are difficult to compare from Indy to now because of the La D\\u00c3\\u00a9fense Arena pool, which produced a lot ofslow performances and some erratic results. Place matters more than time at the Olympics anyway, and in general the U.S. did not swim up to its seeding.  Across 35 events, American swimmers finished a combined 89 places lower than their seeding on the pre-meet entry list\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094an average drop of 2.5 spots. The women fared considerably better than the men in that regard, while also winning five golds to the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s two (one was shared in the mixed medley relay).  A few extreme busts skew the seeding number slightly, when other metrics make the overall performance look slightly less drastic. For instance, five times Americans were seeded to win medals and missed the podium, while three Americans took home hardware who were not expected to, according to seeding.  Still, the overall picture of underperformance is pretty clear, and the sky-high U.S. standards don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t allow for much in the way of underperforming. Swimming might only be second to basketball in terms of the public demand to dominate at the Olympics.  American male headliner Caeleb Dressel, who bounced back from a two-event debacle Friday to swim a very good butterfly leg on the medley relay, spoke two truths that are in conflict with each other: the standards aren\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t changing in the U.S. and the world is catching up.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t a bad meet at all,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d said Dressel, who has won nine Olympic medals, eight of them gold. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe goal when you come to the Olympics and World Championships is gold medals. There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s other countries that are getting very dominant. The wealth has just been spread around. I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t think we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re getting any worse, per se.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t think the goals need to change because the world is getting faster.\\u00c2\\u00a0 I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t think we start striving for silver and bronze\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094not that there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s anything wrong with that, but we want to be the most dominant team. And we were at these Games.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The margins were just smaller. And truth be told, the U.S. went into the weekend needing to swim very well to salvage anything positive from this meet.  That largely happened. On SaturdayKatie Ledecky did what she does, winning the 800 freestyle, and then the mixed medley relay came through. And on Sunday, Finke and the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s relay sandwiched some heroics around another otherworldly Chinese performance.  Leading up to his race, Finke was well aware ofAmerica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s no-gold individual performance by the men. Not one to shy away from what many athletes would call \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009coutside noise\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said he actually dove into the comments section on the niche website Swimswam.com.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI like reading that stuff,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Finke said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt kind of motivates me inside.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  That said, Finke also acknowledged feeling pressure. After winning both the 800 and 1,500 in Tokyo three years ago, he couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t quite rally to catch Ireland\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daniel Wiffen in the shorter of the two races earlier in the week. So he got on the blocks for the 1,500 and just went for it.  That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a scary strategy in the longest pool race, one that can come at a heavy cost. And it runs counter to Finke\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s trademark, late-charging style. But with everything on the line he just tossed aside caution and attacked from the very first stroke.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat really was not my strategy going into the race,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he acknowledged with a laugh. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know how the race was going to play out. I kind of saw I had a pretty decent lead at the 300 so I knew I had to keep going and make the guys hurt a little bit. They started to catch up to me and I was getting a little worried, so I knew I had to keep pushing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Wiffen and, more pertinently, Italy\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Gregorio Paltrinieri, were the ones trying to catch Finke. While his lead was getting smaller, his pace ahead of world-record time was getting larger. The crowd got behind Finke\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s record pursuit in the latter stages.  But Finke was only concerned with finishing first, trying to complete the transformation from a dead closer to a front-runner.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t let go of this now,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he thought to himself. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be the guy who got run down after I do all the running down.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  He ran away instead, scoring the last 50 in trademark Finke fashion to break the 12-year-old world record of China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Sun Yang. In the whack-a-mole game of China and drug testing, removing the controversial Sun from the record books\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s served a drug suspension and been involved in testing brouhahas\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094was followed minutes later by that country winning the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medley.  The race played out as a taut drama between the Chinese, Americans and French, to the roaring delight of the fans.\\u00c2  The Americans went with the quartet of Ryan Murphy, Nic Fink, Caeleb Dressel and Hunter Armstrong and it almost paid off. Murphy and Fink had good opening splits, but not quite as fast as they were Saturday on the front end of the mixed medley\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094they were a combined 1.04 seconds slower, which loomed large in a race decided by .55 seconds.  Dressel had a monster fly leg, clocking a 49.41, but that didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t provide quite enough cushion for Armstrong going up against China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Pan Zhanle, who smashed his own world record in the 100 free earlier in the meetin an eyebrow-raising 46.40 seconds. Pan followed that up with what might be the fastest relay split in human history, dropping a 45.92 to win the race\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s .14 faster than Jason Lezak\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s immortal 100 free split for the U.S. in the 2008 Olympics that kept Michael Phelps\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 drive for eight gold medals alive.  Given China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s drug history, this was not an overwhelmingly popular result. Twenty-three swimmers had positive tests for Trimetazidine in 2021,which was revealed in the spring, and there have been revelations about other positive tests that were kept secret and yielded no penalties. Eleven Chinese swimmers at the Olympics were among those who tested positive in \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009921, and two of those 11 were on the winning relay.  Pan, it should be noted, was not one of them. But his times have been a source of great discussion. Without sounding at all accusatory, Dressel said Pan\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100 freestyle world record swim here was one of two in modern times that made his \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cjaw drop,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d with the other being Adam Peaty\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100 breastroke world record in 2020.  The question was asked of the American relay about losing to China, and Fink stepped in to answer it for Dressel. He answered about shortcomings by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) in general, not China.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s questions about the system,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Fink said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIs WADA doing everything it can? We want more clarity and transparency on all this stuff. Nothing against the athletes competing, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just questions about the system. It seems like there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s cycle after cycle of concerns and questions.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Following that race, the American women finished an overall positive meet with a thunderclap of a relay. Backstroker Regan Smith, breastroker Lilly King, butterflyer Gretchen Walsh and freestyler Torri Huske made sure it wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t close, with King breaking it open and the lead growing from there.\\u00c2  It was a nice valedictory moment for King, who is in the last of her three Olympics. The other three figure to be mainstays of the American team through 2028.  The present and future on the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s side is bright. The men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s side should improve after being caught in a bit of a generation gap in 2024\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094there is a youth movement coming, some of which got valuable Olympic experience here.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThose guys are kind of getting a taste for it now, they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re going to be in the hunt for gold, for sure,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Fink said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re excited for them.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  For now, though, USA Swimming exits Paris with a mixed bag of results that didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t live up to the traditional standard. There will be changes ahead, because a mixed bag won\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t cut it at a home Olympics in 2028.\\u00c2  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Pat Forde is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated who covers college football and college basketball as well as the Olympics and horse racing. He cohosts the College Football Enquirer podcast and is a football analyst on the Big Ten Network. He previously worked for Yahoo Sports, ESPN and The (Louisville) Courier-Journal. Forde has won 28 Associated Press Sports Editors writing contest awards, has been published three times in the Best American Sports Writing book series, and was nominated for the 1990 Pulitzer Prize. A past president of the U.S. Basketball Writers Association and member of the Football Writers Association of America, he lives in Louisville with his wife. They have three children, all of whom were collegiate swimmers.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"